Rising film director, Dotun Ololade has opened up about his new project, ‘Stupid Finder.’ Ololade, a co-director of the buzzing short film, ‘Stupid Finder,’ highlighted the purpose of the film in a brief chat with The Nation. “What we did with Stupid Finder is simple; we used storytelling to engage the Nigerian communities on complex social issues, in a way that is relatable and make sense of the issues we are addressing,” he said.   Why Rema, Zlatan are major spenders at Flykicks, by Otukpa     Wale Bouncer speaks on proposed US tour with Portable,…     AMAA 2022: Organisers extend entry submission to June 15   Continuing, he said, “It is an incredible honour to be part of this production and I am so humbled by the opportunity to direct this amazing project and work with the cast and crew.” Written by Hope Matthew and directed by Dotun Ololade and Sylvester Ahonsi, ‘Stupid Finder’ has created a lot of buzz since its premiere on May 5. Raking in a total of eight awards at the EbonyLife Creative Academy graduation in 2022, the short film talks about brotherhood and new path discovery. The film features Ezekiel Abayomi, Akorede Ajayi, Ayodeji Adejumo, and Joy Chioma Obilo.  One of the co-producers Eric Nwanso said the short film puts a unique narrative around the nature of truth in the lives and challenges of the lower social class in Nigeria. Other producers of the short film are Lawrence Iweriebor, Imoh Eboh, and Stephanie Ugbeye.